{n}Plaintiff re-alleges and incorporates by reference each of the allegations of the Complaint contained in the preceding paragraphs, as if fully set forth herein.
{n}Plaintiff and Defendant Braham are in landlord-tenant relationships created by a written lease agreement.
{n}Plaintiff alleges that Defendant shut off all power to the Unit, allegedly in order to perform Primary Renovation Work. Yet, this was done in violation the Tenant Habitability Plan (hereinafter, "THP") and the applicable Rent Adjustment Comission (hereinafter, "RAC") Regulations in numerous ways, including, but not limited to:
• Failing, before beginning work on the Property, to obtain permits as required by Section 152.03.A.1, including, but not limited to, building permits for alteration of any building or structure, plumbing permits, and installation permits;
• Failing, before beginning work on the Property, to submit and have accepted by L.A.H.D. a Tenant Habitability Plan for the Primary Renovation Work undertaken, as set forth in Section 152.03.B, which requires, among other things: identification of the landlord and general contractor(s) responsible for the work; identification of all affected tenants; description of the scope of the work; identification of the impact of the work on the habitability of the premises, as well as on tenants’ personal property; and identification of mitigation measures to be adopted to ensure tenants are not required to occupy an untenantable dwelling, and to ensure that their personal property will be protected from reasonably foreseeable damage or loss;
• Failing, at least 60 days before beginning work on the Property, to provide Plaintiff with a Notice of the Primary Renovation Work listing the estimated start and completion dates of the work; a description of the work and its impact; the details of temporary relocation, if required, notice of the tenants’ right to appeal, and notice to the tenants of their right to “reoccupy the units under the existing terms of tenancy upon completion of Primary Renovation Work subject to rent adjustment authorized under this chapter” as outlined in Section 152.03.D;
• Failing, before beginning work on the Property, to wait until 60 days after the THP was approved by L.A.H.D.;
• Failing, before beginning work on the Property, to provide Plaintiff with either temporary or permanent relocation assistance in the manner and amount provided for by L.A.M.C. section 152.06;
• Failing, before beginning work on the Property, to provide transportation, temporary storage, and protection from reasonably foreseeable damage to, or loss/theft of, Plaintiff’s personal property, including furnishings;
{n}Based on Defendant’s willful failure to provide relocation assistance, Plaintiff is entitled to damages in the amount of the unpaid relocation assistance, together with reasonable attorneys’ fees and costs, pursuant to L.A.M.C. section 152.07.D.
{n}Based on Defendant’s willful breach of requirements to comply with the payment obligations, to provide safe, decent and sanitary temporary replacement housing, and/or to allow a tenant to reoccupy a rental unit once the primary work is completed, Plaintiff is entitled to all actual damages, special damages of up to three times the amount of actual damages, and reasonable attorneys’ fees, and costs, pursuant to L.A.M.C. section 152.07.E.

{n}Plaintiff repeats, re-alleges, and incorporates by reference, each and every allegation set forth above.
{n}The acts of Defendants Ms. Bills and WIB described above constitute violations of the Harassment Ordinance as follows:
A. Defendants failed to perform repairs and maintenance required by contract or by State, County or local housing, health or safety laws, in violation of S.M.M.C. § 4.56.020 (b);
B. Defendants failed to exercise due diligence in completing repairs and maintenance once undertaken, in violation of S.M.M.C. § 4.56.020 (c);
C. Defendants attempted to influence Ms. St. James to vacate her rental unit through intimidation or coercion, in violation of S.M.M.C. § 4.56.020 (f);
D. Defendants violated laws which prohibit discrimination based on age or disability, in violation of S.M.M.C. § 4.56.020 (h);
E. Defendants interfered with Plaintiffs respective rights to quiet and use and enjoyment of her unit in violation of S.M.M.C. § 4.56.020 (i);
F. Defendants interfered with Ms. St. James' right to privacy, including, but not limited to, entering or photographing portions of a rental housing unit that are beyond the scope of a lawful entry or inspection in violation of S.M.M.C. § 4.56.020 (1).
{n}For each act of wrongful harassment, the Defendants are liable for the remedies established in S.M.M.C. § 4.56.040(c)-(e).
{n}Pursuant to S.M.M.C. § 4.56.040 (d), Defendants are jointly and severally liable, for each separate act in violation of the Harassment Ordinance, for statutory damages in the sum of $10,000; additional civil penalties of up to $5,000 since the Plaintiff is over sixty-five and disabled, and for attorneys' fees and costs. Each of the Defendants is individually liable for each and every violation regardless of whether she or it personally committed the violation.
{n}As a senior and disabled person, Plaintiff is entitled to an amount up to three times the penalty imposed by the Tenant Harassment Ordinance, pursuant to Civil Code § 3345, because (i) Defendants knew or should have known that their conduct was directed to a senior and disabled person; (ii) as a direct result of Defendants' conduct, Plaintiff stands to lose her Housing Choice Voucher, which are payments under a government benefits program; and/or (iii) Plaintiff is substantially more vulnerable than other members of the public to Defendants' conduct because of her age, poor health, and disability, and she has actually suffered substantial emotional and economic damage resulting from Defendants' conduct.
{n}The Court may award punitive damages pursuant to S.M.M.C. § 4.56.040 (d). This is an appropriate case for punitive damages because, among other things, the Defendants' actions were deliberate, willful, malicious and in conscious disregard of Plaintiffs rights. Defendants took advantage of Plaintiffs vulnerabilities, namely that she is disabled, elderly and extremely low-income. Furthermore, Defendants engaged in prior unlawful acts of harassment against Plaintiff and against other tenants.
{n}Unless the defendants are enjoined from this misconduct, Ms. St. James, as well as other current and future tenants at the Second Street Property and Defendants' other residential properties, are likely to suffer irreparable injury in the loss of their legal rights.
{n}The Defendants have committed acts of harassment, proposed to commit acts of harassment, and engaged in a pattern and practice of tenant harassment, all of which violated, and continue to violate, S.M.M.C. § 4.56.020. Injunctive relief is expressly authorized by S.M.M.C. § 4.56.040 (c).
